    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-identifying-indirect-proportions-in-real-life-situations">
        <title>Identifying Indirect Proportionscin Real Life Situations</title>

        <activity>
            <title>Work in Groups</title>
            
            <p>
                Consider a number of learners sharing 40 biscuits as shown in the table below
            </p>
            
            <table>
                <title>Biscuits sharing table</title>
                <tabular left="medium" right="medium" top="medium" bottom="medium">
                    <row halign="center" header="no">
                        <cell>Number of learners</cell>
                        <cell>1</cell>
                        <cell>2</cell>
                        <cell>4</cell>
                        <cell>5</cell>
                        <cell>8</cell>
                        <cell>10</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>Amout of biscuits</cell>
                        <cell>40</cell>
                        <cell>20</cell>
                        <cell>10</cell>
                        <cell>8</cell>
                        <cell>5</cell>
                        <cell>4</cell>
                    </row>
                </tabular>
            </table>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Work the ratios of learners to bisuits from the first row.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Compute the variations of obtained in the row.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Discuss with others how the ratios are changing.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </activity>

        <p>
            <md>
                <mrow> \amp {\color{blue} \text{Learning Point}} </mrow>
            </md>
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>{\color{green} \text{An indirect proportion is identified when two quantities are such that if one quantity increases in a particualr ratio, 
            then the other quantity decreases in the same ratio.}}</m>
        </p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    The table below shows corresponding quantities <m>x</m> and <m>y.</m>
                </p>

                <table>
                    <title></title>
                    <tabular left="medium" right="medium" bottom="medium" top="medium">
                        <row halign="center" header="yes">
                            <cell><em>x</em></cell>
                            <cell>200</cell>
                            <cell>300</cell>
                            <cell>500</cell>
                            <cell>600</cell>
                            <cell>900</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell><em>y</em></cell>
                            <cell>4.5</cell>
                            <cell>3</cell>
                            <cell>1.8</cell>
                            <cell>1.5</cell>
                            <cell>1</cell>
                        </row>
                    </tabular>
                </table>

                <p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Find the ratio of the;
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <ol>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                            <m>1^st</m> value of <m>x</m> to the <m>2^nd</m> value.
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                            <m>2^nd</m> value of <m>x</m> to the <m>4^th</m> value.
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li>
                                        <p>
                                            <m>3^rd</m> value of <m>x</m> to the <m>5^th</m> value.
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                </ol>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Find he ratios of the corresponding values of <m>y</m> for the values of <m>x</m> in (a).
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                State whether <m>x</m> is inversely proportional to <m>y.</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>200:300 = \amp \frac{200}{100}:\frac{300}{100} </mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>= \amp 2:3 </mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>300:600 = \amp \frac{300}{600} </mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>= \amp 1:2 </mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>500:900 = \amp \frac{500}{100}:\frac{900}{100} </mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>= \amp 5:9 </mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        
    </subsubsection>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-working-out-indirect-proportions-in-real-life-situations">
        <title>Working Out Indirect Proportions in Real Life Situations</title>

        <activity>
            <title>Work in Groups.</title>
            
            <p>
                Consider the following table showing time in hours taken to cover a distance of <m>100</m> <em>km</em> at various speeds in kilometers per hour.
            </p>

            <table>
                <title>Time and Speed table</title>
                <tabular left="medium" right="medium" top="medium" bottom="medium">
                    <row halign="center" header="yes">
                        <cell>Time <em>(hours)</em></cell>
                        <cell>1</cell>
                        <cell>2</cell>
                        <cell>4</cell>
                        <cell>5</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>Speed <em>(km/h)</em></cell>
                        <cell>100</cell>
                        <cell>50</cell>
                        <cell>25</cell>
                        <cell>20</cell>
                    </row>
                </tabular>
            </table>

            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Find the ratio of any two quantities in the first row (time).
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Find the ratio of the corresponding speeds.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Find the product of the corresponding quantities.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Discuss and share your findings with other groups.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </activity>

        <p>
            <md>
                <mrow> \amp {\color{blue} \text{Learning Point}} </mrow>
            </md>
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>{\color{green} \text{The ratio in an indirect poportion is used to find a quantity when the corresponding quantity is given.}}</m>
        </p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Umu takes three days to weed a garden. She works for eaight hours a day.
                    Find how long i would take her to weed the same gardeen working six hours a day.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    In this case the number of days she takes increases as time per day reduces/decreases in the same ratio.
                </p>
                <p>
                    The ratio for the time in hours is
                    <me>
                        8:6
                    </me>                
                </p>
                <p>
                    Let thw number of days be <m>x</m> when working for 6 hours a day.
                </p>
                <p>
                    The ratio for the days is
                    <me>
                        3:y
                    </me>                
                </p>
                <p>
                    Therefore,
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\farc{8}{6} = \amp \frac{y}{3} </mrow>
                    </md>                                
                </p>
                <p>
                    Cross multiplying we have;
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>6y = \amp 24 </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Dividing both side by <m>6</m>, we have;
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>y = \amp 4 </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Therefore, it would takes her four days to weed the garden woking six hours a day.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Ten men take <m>12</m> days to complete a task. 
                    How long will eigth men take to complete the task?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The number of men decreases in the ratio <m>8:10.</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Therefore, the number of days taken increase in the ratio <m>10:8</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    The number of days <m>8</m> men can take is given as;
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>= \amp 12 \times \frac{10}{8} </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>= \amp 15 \text{days}</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        
    </subsubsection>
    
    
